\title{multifer: Typed Perturbation Inference for Projector-Based Multivariate Models}
\description{
A shape-first inference layer for projector-based multivariate models.
Provides one coherent system for component significance, variable and
score stability, and subspace uncertainty across one-block, cross-block,
multiblock, and generalized-eigen shapes.
}
\details{
The framework is built on four principles:
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Typed shapes} — every inferential object is a triple
\verb{(geometry, relation, design)} rather than a bare "shape".
\item \strong{Strict dispatch} — \code{infer()} errors on ambiguous adapters
instead of silently guessing between e.g. PLS-like and CCA-like
inference.
\item \strong{Machine-enforced validity} — adapters declare capabilities and
checked assumptions; the framework refuses to produce \code{"exact"} or
\code{"conditional"} significance output unless those assumptions pass.
\item \strong{Latent units} — result tables key off \code{unit_id}, which may be a
singleton component or a subspace of tied roots, so tied-root
handling is honest by default.
}
